Treat high Cardinality¶














Function to help us bucket all features with count less that given number into a single group













In [65]:



    


def grouper(df, col, cutoff, replace_txt):
    count = df[col].value_counts()
    tmp_list = list(count[count > cutoff].keys())
    df[col] = df[col].map(lambda x: not_replace_value(x, replace_txt, tmp_list))

    return df

def not_replace_value(x, replace_val, lst):
    if x in lst:
        return x
    else:
        return replace_val



    















Plan is to go through all features with high cardinality and decrease number of distinct values. 
General rule I followed was to group into 'Other' all values with low number of counts based on data distribution

Model Selection¶














As far as modeling options, given the provided data these are the ones I think we could realistically create:


There are defnitely more options but from an initial pass these are my recommendations:


    

  • Solve for repair_type (Type of repair: Hard/Soft) - Binary Classification 
    • 

  • Solve for repeat_ct (Number of additional visits: 0-4) - Multiclass or Binary Classification or Regression
    • 

  • Solve for contact_manager_flag (Whether Manager escalation occured: 0/1) - Binary Classification 
    • 

  • Solve for parts_sent (Which parts were sent to solve issue: HDD,LCD,etc.) - Multiclass or Binary Classification 
    • 

  • Solve for repeat_parts_sent (Which parts were sent on repeat call: HDD,Keyboard,etc.) - Multiclass or Binary Classification 
    • 

  • Solve for parts_ct (Number of parts sent to fix issue: 0-40) - Multiclass or Binary Classification or Regression
    • 

  • Solve for topic_category (Which type of problem was identified: Boot,HDD,etc.) - Multiclass Classification 
    • 
















Due to time limitation I will only create one of these of models, however any of these could be easily developed folowing same methodology.

Deployment Plan¶














As far as deploying above model the following steps would need to be taken:


    

  • Modularize code (split into .py files in meaningful sections (Data Intake, Feature Engineering, Modeling))
    • 

  • Persist model, features used and encoding details (.pkl, .xml, yaml files)
    • 

  • Decide on delivery mechanism (email, dashboard, integration with client front-end, etc.)
    • 

  • Establish frequency of predictions and storage
    • 

  • Architect solution taking into account end user desires and available technology
    • 

  • Design production pipeline for live data refresh
    • 

  • Develop model monitoring framework
    • 

  • Continuously iterate and improve solution leveraging user feedback
    • 































Success Metrics¶














A very important aspect of every ML project is capturing it's impact.


In order to do so Sucess Metrics or KPI's must be defined.


Additionally a Pilot or test period must be agreed upon and implemented to ensure model usefulness before rolling out to entire client base.


In this project where we predict the case repair type (Hard/Soft) some metrics that could be calcuated are:


    

  • Percent of True Positives or Cases that were predicted as Hardware repairs and where actually Hardware repairs (ensure that is above a number agreed with business)
    • 

  • Percent of True Positives or Cases that were predicted as Software repairs and where actually Software repairs (ensure that is above a number agreed with business)
    • 

  • Calculate difference in overall case completion time between cases that received alerts and those that didnt.
    •
